# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: joshua-lederberg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The **1958 Nobel Prize in Literature** was awarded the Soviet-Russian author Boris Pasternak (1890–1960) "for his important achievement both in contemporary lyrical poetry and in the field of the great Russian epic tradition." He is the second Russian-language writer to be awarded with such honor.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Pasternak first accepted the prize honour, but was then pressured by the Soviet Union authorities to decline the prize.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1988, Pasternak's son accepted the prize on his behalf.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Boris Pasternak's modernist-leaning poetry first came to light in the 1910s and 1920s, when he published collections of poems such as *Sestra moya—zhizn* ("My Sister, Life", 1922) and *Vtoroe rozhdenie* ("A Second Birth", 1932).
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] He began to emphasize social issues more and use clearer, simpler language in the 1930s.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The existential is another theme in Pasternak's writings, covering nature, life, humanity, and love.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The renowned 1957 novel Doctor Zhivago, which takes place between the socialist revolution of 1905 and World War II, demonstrates this.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Pasternak earned 9 nominations in total.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] He was first introduced for the Nobel Prize in 1946 by English literary critic Maurice Bowra.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] In 1958, after receiving three recommendations from Renato Poggioli, Harry Levin and Ernest Simmons, he was eventually awarded thereafter.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] There were only five women authors nominated: Karen Blixen, Edith Sitwell, Elizabeth Bowen, Gertrud von le Fort and Marie Under.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The authors Eleanor Hallowell Abbott, Zoe Akins, Mary Ritter Beard, Til Brugman, James Branch Cabell, Rachel Crothers, Anurupa Debi, Lionel Giles, Feodor Gladkov, Michael Joseph, Henry Kuttner, Cyril M.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Kornbluth, Irene Lisboa, Dorothy Macardle, Rose Macaulay, George Edward Moore, George Jean Nathan, Seumas O'Sullivan, Elliot Paul, Máiréad "Peig" Sayers, Robert W.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Service, John Collings Squire, Marie Stopes, Ralph Waldo Trine, Ethel Turner, Alfred Weber, and Geoffrey Willans died in 1958 without having been nominated for the award.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The French literary scholar Fernand Baldensperger died before the only chance to be rewarded.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The main contenders for the prize in 1958 were the Danish author Karen Blixen, Italian novelist Alberto Moravia and Boris Pasternak.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] Pasternak's recently published novel *Doctor Zhivago* was decisive for the Nobel committee to unanimously propose Pasternak for the prize he was eventually awarded.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Nobel prize archives shows that no political aspects regarding Pasternak's candidacy were taken in consideration by the Nobel committee during the deliberations and that he was awarded purely on literary merits.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] According to the *New York Times*, the members of the Swedish Academy voted unanimously to award Pasternak.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The choice of Pasternak was heavily criticized by the communist Soviet Union authorities who pressured Pasternak to declined the prize.
[src:joshua-lederberg/1958-nobel-prize-in-literature] The Swedish primer minister Tage Erlander condemned the Soviet reactions, but also criticized the Swedish Academy for their "wholly (or at least predominantly) political" reasons to award Pasternak.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Previously at the University of California, Berkeley, he served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] His academic research focuses on nanomaterials, particularly nanocrystal fabrication for biomedical and renewable energy applications.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Paul Alivisatos was born in Chicago, Illinois, where he lived until the age of 10, when his family moved to Athens, Greece.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He returned to the United States to attend the University of Chicago in the late 1970s.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos received a Bachelor of Arts degree (with honors) with a major in chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1981 and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1986.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral advisor at Berkeley was Charles B.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral thesis was titled *The photophysical properties of molecules near metal and semiconductor surfaces*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] After receiving his doctorate, Alivisatos joined AT&T Bell Labs working with Louis E.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Brus, and began research in the field of nanotechnology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos returned to the University of California, Berkeley in 1988 as an assistant professor of chemistry.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He was promoted to associate professor in 1993 and to full professor in 1995.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In administrative roles, Alivisatos served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as the university's interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In August 2013, he was appointed as Samsung Distinguished Professor in Nanoscience and Nanotechnology Research.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He was also the founding director of the Kavli Energy Nanosciences Institute (ENSI).
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos joined the Materials Sciences Division at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 1991.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He served as associate laboratory director for physical sciences from 2005 to 2007.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In 2008, he became deputy director, and he stepped in as interim director after Steven Chu left to become United States Secretary of Energy under the first Obama administration.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] On November 19, 2009, Alivisatos was appointed 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He refocused the lab on renewable energy and climate research, oversaw new facilities, deepened ties to the national innovation ecosystem, and advanced collaborations that sped technology transfer across industries from autos to medicine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] On March 23, 2015, he announced that he would step down from the directorship once a successor was named.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] On February 26, 2021, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago named Alivisatos as the incoming 14th president of the University of Chicago, with his term beginning on September 1, 2021.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He succeeded Robert Zimmer, who served as the university president from July 2006 to August 2021.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to the office of the president, he was named the John D.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] MacArthur Distinguished Service Professor, chair of the Board of Governors of Argonne National Laboratory, and chair of the Board of Directors of Fermi Forward Discovery Group LLC, which operates the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] On September 24, 2025, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago extended Alivisatos's presidency through June 2030.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is an internationally recognized authority on nano chemistry in the synthesis of semiconductor quantum dots and multi-shaped artificial nanostructures.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Further, he is a world expert on the chemistry of nanoscale crystals; one of his papers (Science, 271: 933–937, 1996) has been cited over 13,800 times.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He is also an expert on how these can be applied, for example as biological markers (e.g., Science, 281: 2013–16, 1998; a paper cited over 10,900 times).
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition, his use of DNA in this area (DNA nanotechnology) has shown the surprising versatility of this molecule.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He has used it to direct crystal growth and create new materials, as in Nature, 382: 609–11, 1996, and even to measure nanoscale distances (see Nature Nanotechnology, 1: 47–52, 2006).
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In February 2011, Alivisatos was ranked fifth among the world's top 100 chemists for the period 2000–2010 in the list released by Thomson Reuters.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He is widely recognized as being the first to demonstrate that semiconductor nanocrystals can be grown into complex two-dimensional shapes, as opposed to simple one-dimensional spheres.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos proved that controlling the growth of nanocrystals is the key to controlling both their size and shape.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] This achievement altered the nanoscience landscape and paved the way for a slew of new potential applications, including biomedical diagnostics, revolutionary photovoltaic cells, and LED materials.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Given that a nanocrystal is virtually all surface and no interior, its properties can vary considerably as the crystal grows in size.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Prior to Alivisatos's research, all non-metal nanocrystals were dot-shaped, meaning they were essentially one-dimensional.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] No techniques had been reported for making two-dimensional or rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals that would also be of uniform size.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] However, in a landmark paper that appeared in the March 2, 2000, issue of the journal Nature, Alivisatos reported on techniques used to select the size but vary the shapes of the nanocrystals produced.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] This was hailed as a major breakthrough in nanocrystal fabrication because rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals can be stacked to create nano-sized electronic devices.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos went on to use his techniques to create an entirely new generation of hybrid solar cells that combined nanotechnology with plastic electronics.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding scientist of Quantum Dot Corporation, a company that makes crystalline nanoscale tags that are used in the study of cell behavior.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] (Quantum Dot is now part of Life Technologies.) He also founded the nanotechnology company Nanosys, and Solexant, a photovoltaic start-up that has since restarted as Siva Power.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding editor of *Nano Letters*, a publication of the American Chemical Society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He formerly served on the Senior Editorial Board of *Science*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He has also served on the editorial advisory boards of*ACS Nano*, the *Journal of Physical Chemistry*, *Chemical Physics*, the *Journal of Chemical Physics*, and *Advanced Materials*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to those listed above, Alivisatos has held fellowships with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Physical Society (1996), and the American Chemical Society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] He is a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:joshua-lederberg/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is married to Nicole Alivisatos, a retired chemist, former editor of the journal Nano Letters, and daughter of the noted chemist, Gábor A.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:joshua-lederberg/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was born to Ambrose and Maggie (Nolan) Cameron in Brookhaven, Mississippi, on March 8, 1924.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She was the second child and the oldest daughter of eight children.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She moved with her family to Chicago in 1930 when she was six years old.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] The family relocated in hopes of finding better job opportunities during the Great Depression.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] However, obtainable jobs for African Americans at this time were hard to come by.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt, a postal finance clerk, on May 12, 1940.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] With Claude she had two sons, Renaldo Wyatt and Claude S.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She raised several of her younger siblings after her mother died at the age of 39 and her father was unable to care for them because of illness.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] After her marriage, Wyatt applied for a job as a typist for Armour and Company in 1941.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] On her first day of work, she discovered African American women were not hired as typists in the front office and instead was sent to the canning department to pack stew in cans for the army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In the early 1950s, Wyatt joined the United Packinghouse Workers of America upon discovering the union did not discriminate against its members.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] As the forefront leader of black women within unions, she and others took advantage of their union's antiracist and antidiscrimination bylaws and fought race-based and gender-based inequities at work as well as in their communities.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1955, Wyatt worked full-time on staff for the UPWA, representing workers across a five-state region.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She recognized the importance and effectiveness of interracial organization.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Among other achievements, Wyatt and her union of black, white, and Latino laborers were able to win "equal pay for equal work" provisions in many union contracts well before the passing of the Equal Pay Act of 1963.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1953, Wyatt was "elected vice president of her branch, Local 56, becoming the first black woman to hold senior office in an American labor union." Wyatt was the director of the Women's Affairs and Human Rights departments of the Amalgamated Meat Cutters.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] By 1956, Wyatt was the Program Coordinator for District One of the UPWA.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] This was also the year the Wyatts began their work with Dr.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Martin Luther King Jr, with whom they helped raise funds for the Montgomery Improvement Association.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In the early 1960s, Eleanor Roosevelt recognized her leadership abilities and appointed her to a position on the Labor Legislation Committee of the United States Commission on the Status of Women.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] African American women, with Addie Wyatt at the helm, had the unparalleled experience of working on the floors of the meatpacking plants as well as being integral parts of building the unions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] During the 1970s she became a powerful figure in the United Food and Commercial Workers International Union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] During this time, she worked harder to create unions that were more inclusive of minorities.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] This not only led African Americans to great confidence within the labor force, but also to women in general becoming financially independent and effective contributors of the economy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1974, Wyatt co-founded the Coalition of Labor Union Women in order to create a stronger, more effective voice for women in the labor movement.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] When Wyatt became the international vice president of the United Food and Commercial Workers in 1976 she was the first African-American woman to take a high-level leadership position in an international union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She fought for human rights on three fronts; as a laborer, as a woman, and as an African American.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1955, Wyatt was ordained as a Church of God minister.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Together with her husband, also an ordained Church of God minister, she worked in the ministry and civil rights campaign of Dr.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Martin Luther King Jr. and participated in major civil rights marches, including the March on Washington, and the march from Selma to Montgomery, Alabama.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was involved in grassroots civil rights work in Chicago and participated in organizing protests.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She was a labor adviser to the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC).
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She served on the Action Committee of the Chicago Freedom Movement.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In the 1960s, Wyatt was active in Operation Breadbasket, which distributed food to underprivileged people across the United States.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1955, the Wyatts founded the Vernon Park Church of God (Anderson, Indiana) in Chicago.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] The church began in a small, oil stained floor, house garage (located at 90th Vernon in Chicago) with a congregation made up only of the Wyatts' children, siblings and a few close faithful friends.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1984, Wyatt became a full-time minister, and was appointed by her husband to serve as Co-Pastor of the church, working faithfully alongside him.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] The couple's ministry together spanned 44 years, during which time the Wyatts' church matriculated from the small house garage, to a storefront above a furniture store on 74th Cottage Grove (Chicago), from there on to their first church built from the ground at 7653 S.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Maryland Avenue (Chicago), and then finally on to their second church built from the ground located at 9011 S.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Stony Island Avenue (Chicago), which included a 1000-seat Sanctuary edifice with classrooms and an industrial sized kitchen.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] It was at this location that the Wyatts pastored faithfully until illness overtook their bodies, causing them to retire from pastoring in 2000.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Although retired from pastoring, the Wyatts continued to faithfully attend and serve within their church worship services until their deaths.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1999, Wyatt was the founder and CEO of the Wyatt Family Community Center in Chicago, the church's multipurpose community center which served the community and the nation through its diverse programming for families.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was a founding member of the National Organization for Women.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was a co-founded of the Coalition of Labor Union Women with Willa Mae Sudduth in 1974.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was named one of *Time* magazine's Women of the Year in 1975.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] The publication recognized her for "speaking out effectively against sexual and racial discrimination in hiring, promotion and pay." Wyatt's picture appeared on the magazine's cover along with First Lady Betty Ford, tennis great Billie Jean King, and Rep.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Barbara Jordan, one of the first black women elected to Congress.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] She was inducted as an Honorary member of Delta Sigma Theta sorority in 1983.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] From 1980 to 1984 she was one of *Ebony* magazine's 100 most influential black Americans.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] In 1987, the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists established the Addie L.
[src:joshua-lederberg/addie-l-wyatt] Wyatt was inducted as a Laureate of The Lincoln Academy of Illinois and awarded the Order of Lincoln (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in 2003 in the area of Religion and Labor.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), General Wilhelm Burgdorf and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:joshua-lederberg/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin was born in Banbury, Oxfordshire, on 5 February 1914.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He was the oldest of three sons of Quakers George Hodgkin and Mary Wilson Hodgkin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] His father was the son of Thomas Hodgkin and had read for the Natural Science Tripos at Cambridge where he had befriended electrophysiologist Keith Lucas.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Because of poor eyesight, he was unable to study medicine and eventually ended up working for a bank in Banbury.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] As members of the Society of Friends, George and Mary opposed the Military Service Act of 1916, which introduced conscription, and had to endure a great deal of abuse from their local community, including an attempt to throw George in one of the town canals.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In 1916, George Hodgkin travelled to Armenia as part of an investigation of distress.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Moved by the misery and suffering of Armenian refugees he attempted to go back there in 1918 on a route through the Persian Gulf (as the northern route was closed because of the October Revolution in Russia).
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He died of dysentery in Baghdad on 24 June 1918, just a few weeks after his youngest son, Keith, had been born.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] From an early life on, Hodgkin and his brothers were encouraged to explore the country around their home, which instilled in Alan an interest in natural history, particularly ornithology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] At the age of 15, he helped Wilfred Backhouse Alexander with surveys of heronries and later, at Gresham's School, he overlapped and spent a lot of time with David Lack.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In 1930, he was the winner of a bronze medal in the Public Schools Essay Competition organised by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Alan started his education at The Downs School where his contemporaries included future scientists Frederick Sanger, Alec Bangham, "neither outstandingly brilliant at school" according to Hodgkin, as well as future artists Lawrence Gowing and Kenneth Rowntree.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] After the Downs School, he went on to Gresham's School where he overlapped with future composer Benjamin Britten as well as Maury Meiklejohn.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He ended up receiving a scholarship at Trinity College, Cambridge in botany, zoology and chemistry.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Between school and college, he spent May 1932 at the Freshwater Biological Station at Wray Castle based on a recommendation of his future Director of Studies at Trinity, Carl Pantin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Smith, whose daughter Dorothy was also married to Alan's uncle Robert Howard Hodgkin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In the autumn of 1932, Hodgkin started as a freshman scholar at Trinity College where his friends included classicists John Raven and Michael Grant, fellow-scientists Richard Synge and John H.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Humphrey, as well as Polly and David Hill, the children of Nobel laureate Archibald Hill.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He took physiology with chemistry and zoology for the first two years, including lectures by Nobel laureate E.D.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] For Part II of the tripos he decided to focus on physiology instead of zoology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Nevertheless, he participated in a zoological expedition to the Atlas Mountains in Morocco led by John Pringle in 1934.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He finished Part II of the tripos in July 1935 and stayed at Trinity as a research fellow.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] During his studies, Hodgkin, who described himself as "having been brought up as a supporter of the British Labour Party" was friends with communists and actively participated in the distribution of anti-war pamphlets.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] At Cambridge, he knew James Klugmann and John Cornford, but he emphasised in his autobiography that none of his friends "made any serious effort to convert me [to Communism], either then or later." From 1935 to 1937, Hodgkin was a member of the Cambridge Apostles.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin started conducting experiments on how electrical activity is transmitted in the sciatic nerve of frogs in July 1934.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He found that a nerve impulse arriving at a cold or compression block, can decrease the electrical threshold beyond the block, suggesting that the impulse produces a spread of an electrotonic potential in the nerve beyond the block.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In 1936, Hodgkin was invited by Herbert Gasser, then director of the Rockefeller Institute in New York City, to work in his laboratory during 1937–38.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] There he met Rafael Lorente de Nó and Kenneth Stewart Cole with whom he ended up publishing a paper.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] During that year he also spent time at the Woods Hole Marine Biological Laboratory where he was introduced to the squid giant axon, which ended up being the model system with which he conducted most of the research that eventually led to his Nobel Prize.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In the spring of 1938, he visited Joseph Erlanger at Washington University in St.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Louis who told him he would take Hodgkin's local circuit theory of nerve impulse propagation seriously if he could show that altering the resistance of the fluid outside a nerve fibre made a difference to the velocity of nerve impulse conduction.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Working with single nerve fibres from shore crabs and squids, he showed that the conduction rate was much faster in seawater than in oil, providing strong evidence for the local circuit theory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] After his return to Cambridge he started collaborating with Andrew Huxley who had entered Trinity as a freshman in 1935, three years after Hodgkin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] With a £300 equipment grant from the Rockefeller Foundation, Hodgkin managed to set up a similar physiology setup to the one he had worked with at the Rockefeller Institute.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He moved all his equipment to the Plymouth Marine Laboratory in July 1939.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] There, he and Huxley managed to insert a fine cannula into the giant axon of squids and record action potentials from inside the nerve fibre.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] They sent a short note of their success to *Nature* just before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Despite his Quaker upbringing, Hodgkin was eager to join the war effort as contact with the Nazis during his stay in Germany in 1932 had removed all his pacifist beliefs.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] His first post was at the Royal Aircraft Establishment where he worked on issues in aviation medicine, such as oxygen supply for pilots at high altitudes and the decompression sickness caused by nitrogen bubbles coming out of the blood.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In February 1940 he transferred to the Telecommunications Research Establishment (TRE) where he worked on the development of centimetric radar, including the design of the village Inn AGLT airborne gun-laying system.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Bowen's group in St Athan in South Wales and lived in a local guest house together with John Pringle and Robert Hanbury Brown.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] The group moved to Swanage in May 1940 where Pringle replaced Bowen as leader of the group.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In March 1941, Hodgkin flew on the test flight of a Bristol Blenheim fitted with the first airborne centimetric radar system.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In February and March 1944, he visited the MIT Radiation Laboratory to help foster the interchange of information on developments in radar between Britain and America.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Providing a readable account of the little-known piece of military history that he was a part of during World War II was a main motivation for Hodgkin to write his autobiography *Chance and Design: Reminiscences of Science in Peace and War*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] As the Allied Forces' invasion of France and their continued advance towards Germany in autumn 1944 suggested an end of the war in the foreseeable future, Hodgkin started to plan his return to a career in research at Cambridge.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Rushton and they published an article on how to calculate a nerve fibre's membrane resistance, membrane capacity, its axoplasm's resistance, and the resistance of the external fluid in which the fibre is placed, from experimental observations.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] After being released from military service in August 1945 upon Adrian's request, Hodgkin was able to restart his experiments in collaboration with Bernard Katz and his pre-war collaborator Andrew Huxley.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] They spent the summers of 1947, 1948, and 1949 at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory where they continued to measure resting and action potentials from inside the giant axon of the squid.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Together with Katz, he provided evidence that the permeability of the neuronal cell membrane for sodium increased during an action potential, thus allowing sodium ions to diffuse inward.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] The data they had obtained in 1949 resulted in a series of five papers published in *The Journal of Physiology* that described what became later known as the Hodgkin–Huxley model of the action potential and eventually earned Hodgkin and Huxley the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Cole they used a technique of electrophysiology, known as the *voltage clamp* to measure ionic currents through the membranes of squid axons while holding the membrane voltage at a set level.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] They proposed that the characteristic shape of the action potential is caused by changes in the selective permeability of the membrane for different ions, specifically sodium, potassium, and chloride.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] A model that relies on a set of differential equations and describes each component of an excitable cell as an electrical element was in good agreement with their empirical measurements.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] The cell membrane depolarisation sequence where a small depolarization leads to an increase in sodium permeability, which leads to influx of sodium ions, which in turn depolarizes the membrane even more is now known as the Hodgkin cycle.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In addition, Hodgkin and Huxley's findings led them to hypothesize the existence of ion channels on cell membranes, which were confirmed only decades later.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Confirmation of ion channels came with the development of the patch clamp leading to a Nobel prize in 1991 for Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, and in 2003 for Roderick MacKinnon.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] After establishing ion movements across a selectively permeable cell membrane as the mechanism of the action potential, Hodgkin turned his attention to how the ionic interchange that occurs during the action potential could be reversed afterwards.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Together with Richard Keynes he demonstrated that in addition to the changes in permeability that lead to an action potential, there is a secretory mechanism that ejects sodium and absorbs potassium against the electrochemical gradients.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] A few years later, the Danish scientist Jens Christian Skou discovered the enzyme Na+/K+-ATPase that uses ATP to export three sodium ions in exchange for two potassium ions that are imported, for which he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1997.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1953 by Lord Adrian.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In October 1961, he was told by Swedish journalists that he, Huxley, and Eccles had been awarded the Nobel Prize.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] This turned out to be a false alarm, however, when shortly thereafter it was announced that the 1961 Prize was awarded to Georg von Békésy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] It was only two years later that Hodgkin, Huxley, and Eccles were finally awarded the Prize "for their discoveries concerning the ionic mechanisms involved in excitation and inhibition in the peripheral and central portions of the nerve cell membrane".
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] During the Nobel Banquet on 10 December 1963, Hodgkin gave the traditional speech on behalf of the three neurophysiologists, thanking the king and the Nobel Committee for Physiology or Medicine for the award.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Incidentally, Hodgkin and his wife attended the Nobel Prize ceremony a second time, three years later, when Hodgkin's father-in-law, Francis Peyton Rous, was awarded the 1966 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] From 1951 to 1969, Hodgkin was the Foulerton Professor of the Royal Society at Cambridge.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In 1970 he became the John Humphrey Plummer Professor of Biophysics at Cambridge.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Around this time he also ended his experiments on nerve at the Plymouth Marine Laboratory and switched his focus to visual research which he could do in Cambridge with the help of others while serving as president of the Royal Society.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Together with Denis Baylor and Peter Detwiler he published a series of papers on turtle photoreceptors.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] From 1970 to 1975 Hodgkin served as the 53rd president of the Royal Society (PRS).
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] During his tenure as PRS, he was knighted in 1972 and admitted into the Order of Merit in 1973.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] From 1978 to 1985 he was the 34th Master of Trinity College, Cambridge.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He served on the Royal Society Council from 1958 to 1960 and on the Medical Research Council from 1959 to 1963.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He was foreign secretary of the Physiological Society from 1961 to 1967.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] A portrait of Hodgkin by Michael Noakes hangs in Trinity College's collection.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] During his stay at the Rockefeller Institute in 1937, Hodgkin got to know the American pathologist Francis Peyton Rous who was later awarded the 1966 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] When Rous invited him for dinner to his home, Hodgkin got to know Rous' daughter, Marni, who was then a student at Swarthmore College.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] He proposed to her before going back to England in 1938, but she rejected him.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] When Hodgkin briefly returned to the US in 1944 (see Wartime activities), they reunited and got married on 31 March.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Their first daughter, Sarah, was born in April 1945, shortly before the Hodgkins moved back to Cambridge.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] They had three more children: Deborah Hodgkin (born 2 May 1947), Jonathan Hodgkin (born 24 August 1949), and Rachel Hodgkin (born June 1951).
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Marni became a Children's Book Editor at Macmillan Publishing Company and a successful writer of children's literature, including *Young Winter's Tales* and *Dead Indeed*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Jonathan Hodgkin became a molecular biologist at Cambridge University.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Deborah Hodgkin is also a successful psychologist.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Thomas Hodgkin (1798–1866), who first described Hodgkin's lymphoma, was Alan Hodgkin's great-uncle.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] Hodgkin suffered from a series of medical problems that began soon after his retirement as Master of Trinity.
[src:joshua-lederberg/alan-hodgkin] In 1989 he had surgery to relieve pressure on the spinal cord from one of the intervertebral discs in his neck, which left him unable to walk without support, and with progressive disablement.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] A 2002 survey ranked Bandura as the fourth most frequently cited psychologist of all time, behind B.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Skinner, Sigmund Freud, and Jean Piaget.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In April 2025, Bandura became the first psychologist with more than a million Google Scholar citations.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] During his lifetime, Bandura was widely described as the greatest living psychologist, and as one of the most influential psychologists of all time.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura was born in Mundare, Alberta, an open town of roughly 400 inhabitants, as the youngest of six children.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The limitations of education in his remote town caused Bandura to become independent and self-motivated in terms of learning, and the primarily-developed traits proved helpful later in his career.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura was of Polish and Ukrainian descent; his father was from Kraków, Poland, while his mother was from Ukraine.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura's parents were a key influence in encouraging him to seek ventures out of the small hamlet they resided in.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The summer after finishing high school, Bandura worked in the Yukon to protect the Alaska Highway against sinking.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura later credited his work in the northern tundra as the origin of his interest in human psychopathology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] His experience in the Yukon, where he was exposed to a subculture of drinking and gambling, helped broaden his perspective and scope of views on life.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura arrived in the United States in 1949 and was naturalized in 1956.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He married Virginia Varns (1921–2011) in 1952, and they raised two daughters, Carol and Mary.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura took psychology courses in college and became passionate about the subject.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He graduated after three years in 1949 with a B.A. from the University of British Columbia, winning the Bolocan Award in psychology, and then moved to the then-epicenter of psychology, the University of Iowa, from where he obtained his M.A. in 1951 and Ph.D. in clinical psychology in 1952.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Arthur Benton was his academic adviser at Iowa, giving Bandura a direct academic descent from William James, while Clark Hull and Kenneth Spence were influential collaborators.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] During his Iowa years, Bandura came to support a style of psychology that sought to investigate psychological phenomena through repeatable, experimental testing.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] His inclusion of such mental phenomena as imagery and representation, and his concept of reciprocal determinism, which postulated a relationship of mutual influence between an agent and its environment, marked a radical departure from the dominant behaviorism of the time.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Upon graduation, he completed his postdoctoral internship at the Wichita Guidance Center.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The following year, 1953, he accepted a teaching position at Stanford University, which he held until he became professor emeritus in 2010.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1974, he was elected president of the American Psychological Association (APA), the world's largest association of psychologists.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura would later state the only reason he agreed to be in the running for the APA election was because he wanted his 15 minutes of fame without any intentions of being elected.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura was initially influenced by Robert Sears' work on familial antecedents of social behavior and identificatory learning and gave up his research of the psychoanalytic theory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He directed his initial research to the role of social modeling in human motivation, thought, and action.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In collaboration with Richard Walters, his first doctoral student, he engaged in studies of social learning and aggression.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Their joint efforts illustrated the critical role of modeling in human behavior and led to a program of research into the determinants and mechanisms of observational learning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The initial phase of Bandura's research analyzed the foundations of human learning and the willingness of children and adults to imitate behavior that they observed in other people, particularly the emotion of aggression.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The research indicated models as an important means for learning new behaviors and for achieving behavioral change in an institutional setting.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Social learning theory posits three regulatory systems that control human behavior.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Response and feedback influences have an important function.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Following a response to a stimulus, the reinforcements, either by experience or by observation, will determine future occurrences of the behavior.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Cognitive functions are important in social learning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] For example, for aggressive behavior to occur, some people are readily angered by the sight or the thought of persons with whom they had hostile encounters, and that aggression-inducing memory is learned.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Social learning theory became one of the theoretical frameworks for Entertainment-Education, a method of creating socially beneficial entertainment pioneered by Miguel Sabido.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura and Sabido went on to forge a close relationship and further refine the theory and practice.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] His research with Walters led to his first book, *Adolescent Aggression* (1959), followed by *Social Learning and Personality Development* (1963), and *Aggression: A Social Learning Analysis* (1973).
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] During a period dominated by behaviorism in the mold of B.F.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Skinner, Bandura believed the sole behavioral modifiers of reward and punishment in classical and operant conditioning were inadequate as a framework, and that many human behaviors were learned from other humans.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura began to analyze the means of treating unduly aggressive children by identifying sources of violence in their lives.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Initial research in the area had begun in the 1940s under Neal Miller and John Dollard; his continued work in this line eventually culminated in the Bobo doll experiment, which led to his 1977 treatise, *Social Learning Theory*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Many of his innovations came from his focus on empirical investigation and reproducible investigation, contrary to Sigmund Freud's popular theories of psychoanalysis.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1974, Stanford University awarded him an endowed chair and he became David Starr Jordan Professor of Social Science in Psychology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1961, Bandura conducted a controversial experiment known as the Bobo doll experiment, which was designed to show that similar behaviors were learned by individuals shaping their own behavior after the actions of models.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The experiment emphasized how young individuals are influenced by the acts of adults.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] When the adults were praised for their aggressive behavior, the children were more likely to keep on hitting the doll.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] However, when the adults were punished, they consequently stopped hitting the doll as well.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura's results from the experiment were widely credited with helping shift the focus in academic psychology from pure behaviorism to cognitive psychology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] By the mid-1980s, Bandura's research had taken a more holistic bent, and his analysis tended toward giving a more comprehensive overview of human cognition in the context of social learning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The theory he expanded from social learning theory soon became known as social cognitive theory.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The foundation of Bandura's social learning theory is the idea that people may learn by seeing and copying the observable behaviors of others.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] As an alternative to the earlier work of colleague psychologist B.F.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Skinner, who was well known for advocating the behaviorist theory, psychologists Bandura and Sears presented the social learning hypothesis.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1986, Bandura published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, in which he re-conceptualized individuals as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, in opposition to the orthodox conception of humans as governed by external forces.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He advanced concepts of triadic reciprocal causation, which determined the connections between human behavior, environmental factors, and personal factors such as cognitive, affective, and biological events, and of reciprocal determinism, governing the causal relations between such factors.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura's emphasis on the capacity of agents to self-organize and self-regulate would eventually give rise to his later work on self-efficacy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] While investigating the processes by which modeling alleviates phobic disorders in snake-phobics, he found that self-efficacy beliefs (which the phobic individuals had in their own capabilities to alleviate their phobia) mediated changes in behavior and in fear-arousal.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He launched a major program of research examining the influential role of self-referent thought in psychological functioning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Although he continued to explore and write on theoretical problems relating to myriad topics, from the late 1970s, he devoted much attention to exploring the role of self-efficacy beliefs in human functioning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1986, he published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, a book in which he offered a social cognitive theory of human functioning that accords a central role to cognitive, vicarious, self-regulatory, and self-reflective processes in human adaptation and change.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] This theory has roots in an agentic perspective that views people as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, not just as reactive organisms shaped by environmental forces or driven by inner impulses.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] His book, *Self-Efficacy: The Exercise of Control* was published in 1997.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] The application of Bandura's self-efficacy research did not end with phobia-mediation, however, but extended into healthcare, particularly in the management of addictive behaviors such as smoking and smoking cessation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In these interventions, an individual's confidence in their ability to resist cravings and high-risk triggers was found to be a strong predictor of relapse.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Successful, long-term maintenance of cessation and positive alterations in usage were consistently associated with higher self-efficacy, suggesting that emphasizing and enhancing one's confidence could reduce rates of relapse.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] These findings validate Bandura's theory and demonstrate ways in which targeting self-efficacy has predicted treatment outcomes in addictive behaviors.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura's social cognitive theories have been applied to education as well, mainly focusing on self-efficacy, self-regulation, observational learning, and reciprocal determinism.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura's research showed that high perceived self-efficacy led teachers and students to set higher goals, and it increased the likelihood that they would dedicate themselves to those goals.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In an educational setting, self-efficacy refers to a student or teacher's confidence to participate in certain actions that will help them achieve distinct goals.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] Bandura died at his home in Stanford, on July 26, 2021, from congestive heart failure, at the age of 95.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1980.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] He received the Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions from the American Psychological Association (APA) in 1980 for pioneering the research in the field of self-regulated learning.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 1999, he received the Thorndike Award for Distinguished Contributions of Psychology to Education from the APA, and in 2001, he received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Association for the Advancement of Behavior Therapy.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 2008, he received the University of Louisville Grawemeyer Award for contributions to psychology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 2014, he was made an Officer of the Order of Canada "for his foundational contributions to social psychology, notably for uncovering the influence of observation on human learning and aggression".
[src:joshua-lederberg/albert-bandura] In 2016, he was awarded the National Medal of Science by president Barack Obama.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In addition to his contributions to biology, Lederberg did extensive research in artificial intelligence.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] This included work in the NASA experimental programs seeking life on Mars and the chemistry expert system Dendral.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Lederberg was born in Montclair, New Jersey, to a Jewish family, son of Esther Goldenbaum Schulman Lederberg and Rabbi Zvi Hirsch Lederberg, in 1925, and moved to Washington Heights, Manhattan as an infant.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Lederberg graduated from Stuyvesant High School in New York City at the age of 15 in 1941.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] After graduation, he was allowed lab space as part of the American Institute Science Laboratory, a forerunner of the Westinghouse Science Talent Search.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He enrolled in Columbia University in 1941, majoring in zoology.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Ryan, he conducted biochemical and genetic studies on the bread mold *Neurospora crassa*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Intending to receive his MD and fulfill his military service obligations, Lederberg worked as a hospital corpsman during 1943 in the clinical pathology laboratory at St.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Albans Naval Hospital, where he examined sailors' blood and stool samples for malaria.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He went on to receive his undergraduate degree in 1944.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Joshua Lederberg began medical studies at Columbia's College of Physicians and Surgeons while continuing to perform experiments.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Inspired by Oswald Avery's discovery of the importance of DNA, Lederberg began to investigate his hypothesis that, contrary to prevailing opinion, bacteria did not simply pass down exact copies of genetic information, making all cells in a lineage essentially clones.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] After making little progress at Columbia, Lederberg wrote to Edward Tatum, Ryan's post-doctoral mentor, proposing a collaboration.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1946 and 1947, Lederberg took a leave of absence to study under the mentorship of Tatum at Yale University.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Lederberg and Tatum showed that the bacterium *Escherichia coli* entered a sexual phase during which it could share genetic information through bacterial conjugation.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] With this discovery and some mapping of the *E. coli* chromosome, Lederberg was able to receive his Ph.D. from Yale University in 1947.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Joshua married Esther Miriam Zimmer (herself a student of Edward Tatum) on December 13, 1946.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Instead of returning to Columbia to finish his medical degree, Lederberg chose to accept an offer of an assistant professorship in genetics at the University of Wisconsin–Madison.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] His wife Esther Lederberg went with him to Wisconsin.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] She received her doctorate there in 1950.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Joshua Lederberg and Norton Zinder showed in 1951 that genetic material could be transferred from one strain of the bacterium *Salmonella typhimurium* to another using viral material as an intermediary step.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Laurance Morse, Esther Lederberg and Joshua Lederberg also discovered specialized transduction.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] The research in specialized transduction focused upon lambda phage infection of *E. coli*.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Transduction and specialized transduction explained how bacteria of different species could gain resistance to the same antibiotic very quickly.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] During her time in Joshua Lederberg's laboratory, Esther Lederberg also discovered fertility factor F, later publishing with Joshua Lederberg and Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1956, the Society of Illinois Bacteriologists simultaneously awarded Joshua Lederberg and Esther Lederberg the Pasteur Medal, for "their outstanding contributions to the fields of microbiology and genetics".
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1957, Joshua Lederberg founded the Department of Medical Genetics at the University of Wisconsin–Madison.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He has held visiting professorship in Bacteriology at the University of California, Berkeley in summer 1950 and University of Melbourne (1957).
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Also in 1957, he was elected to the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1958, Joshua Lederberg received the Nobel Prize and moved to Stanford University, where he was the founder and chairman of the Department of Genetics.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He collaborated with Frank Macfarlane Burnet to study viral antibodies.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] With the launching of *Sputnik* in 1957, Lederberg became concerned about the biological impact of space exploration.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In a letter to the National Academies of Sciences, he outlined his concerns that extraterrestrial microbes might gain entry to Earth onboard spacecraft, causing catastrophic diseases.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He also argued that, conversely, microbial contamination of manmade satellites and probes may obscure the search for extraterrestrial life.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He advised quarantine for returning astronauts and equipment and sterilization of equipment prior to launch.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Teaming up with Carl Sagan, his public advocacy for what he termed exobiology helped expand the role of biology in NASA.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Lederberg was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1959 and the American Philosophical Society in 1960.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In the 1960s, he collaborated with Edward Feigenbaum in Stanford's computer science department to develop DENDRAL.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1978, he became the president of Rockefeller University, until he stepped down in 1990 and became professor-emeritus of molecular genetics and informatics at Rockefeller University, reflecting his extensive research and publications in these disciplines.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Throughout his career, Lederberg was active as a scientific advisor to the U.S. government.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Starting in 1950, he was a member of various panels of the Presidential Science Advisory Committee.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Defense Science Board and the chairman of President Jimmy Carter's President's Cancer Panel.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1989, he received National Medal of Science for his contributions to the scientific world.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In 1994, he headed the Department of Defense's Task Force on Persian Gulf War Health Effects, which investigated Gulf War Syndrome.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] In the 1970s, considerable effort was put towards the developing field of euphenics since it was seen as a positive form of genetic engineering.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] One of the first publicized applications of euphenics was the use of vitamins containing folic acid during pregnancy to combat neural-tube deficiencies such as spina bifida in the 1970s.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] However, medical science had been using euphenic strategies years before the term itself was coined.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Euphenics is used today in the medical community to more generally refer to methods of affecting a genetic condition in a positive manner through diet, lifestyle or environment, such as the use of insulin to control diabetes or installation of a pacemaker to offset a heart defect.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] Lederberg married fellow scientist Esther Miriam Zimmer in 1946; they divorced in 1966.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He married psychiatrist Marguerite Stein Kirsch in 1968.
[src:joshua-lederberg/joshua-lederberg] He was survived by Marguerite, their daughter, Anne Lederberg, and his stepson, David Kirsch.
